crops.description: A palm, native to the Valle del Cauca, which is more ornamental than Guilielma utilis.

crops.institution_involved: Estación Agrícola Experimental, Palmira, Departmento del Valle del Cauca
crops.description: A wild walnut, native to the highlands of northern South America, which resembles closely the black walnut of the United States. The thick-shelled nut contains a kernel of mild pleasant flavor.

crops.institution_involved: Estación Agrícola Experimental, Palmira, Departmento del Valle del Cauca
crops.description: An ornamental vine, native to Colombia, with red flowers which are followed by green fruits about 3 inches long. The seeds are smaller and the pulp is not so highly flavored as in some of the other varieties.

Eriosema sp. Fabaceae. Received under the name Eriosema lejeunei.
Meibomia lasiocarpa (Beauv.) Kuntze. Fabaceae. Collected in the Belgian Congo. For previous introduction see 103618.
Desmodium salicifolium DC. Fabaceae. A bushy shrub with lanceolate-oblong leaflets and flowers in terminal panicles. Native to the East Indies.
Vigna sp. Fabaceae. Collected in Urundi District.

crops.presented_by: Institute of Sub-tropical Cultures, Sukhum, Transcaucasia
crops.description: Arum elongatum Stev. Araceae. An arum from Asia Minor, about a foot high, with brownish, broadly hastate-sagittate leaves. The spathe tube is ob-long ovoid, white within, with the limb intense black purple.

crops.presented_by: Institute of Sub-tropical Cultures, Sukhum, Transcaucasia
crops.description: Colchicum umbrosum Stev. Melanthaceae. Autumn crocus. A low bulbous plant, native to the Caucasus, with about five narrow leaves and small clusters of lilac flowers. For previous introduction see 67014.

crops.presented_by: Institute of Sub-tropical Cultures, Sukhum, Transcaucasia
crops.description: Crocus scharojani Rupr. Iridaceae. A crocus with a very small globose bulb. In the Caucasus region, where it is native, the leaves appear in the spring and remain until the bright-yellow flowers appear the latter part of July and August. The throat of the corolla is yellowish white, the anthers are pale yellow, and the style branches are orange red. For previous introduction see 90616.

crops.presented_by: Institute of Sub-tropical Cultures, Sukhum, Transcaucasia
crops.description: Ornithogalum balansae Boiss. Liliaceae. A low bulbous plant with two or three linear leaves 3 to 4 inches long and small white flowers in a small dense raceme, on a scape about as long as the leaves. Native to Armenia.

crops.presented_by: Institute of Sub-tropical Cultures, Sukhum, Transcaucasia
crops.description: Scilla winogradowii Sosn. Liliaceae. A squill from the Caucasus with one to three pale-blue suberect flowers more than three-fifths of an inch long. The leaves are oblong-linear or linear lanceolate.

Naljara. Collected in the MacDonnell Ranges. A perennial grass with long leafy stolons and short firm leaves. The flowering culms, erect or ascending, are 6 to 18 inches high, and the edible seeds are eaten by the natives.
Chloris virgata Swartz. Poaceae. Feather fingergrass. Collected at Alice Springs. A fine grazing grass.

Dactyloctenium aegyptium (L.) Rich. (Eleusine aegyptiaca Desf.). Collected at Alice Springs. A tropical prostrate annual grass which forms mats by rooting at the nodes. For previous introduction see 73115.
Eragrostis sp. Poaceae. Collected at Alice Springs. A very nutritious fodder.

crops.origin: North of Alice Springs, Northern part of Central Australia
crops.description: Erythrina sp. Fabaceae. Collected north of Alice Springs, in the northern part of central Australia. Ininta, or bean tree. The red seeds of this tree are used as ornaments by the natives, and the wood is used in the manufacture of shields and putchis (vessels) of all kinds. The beanwood is very light, one of the few soft woods found in central Australia.
